cal and artistic revolution. This collection of essays aims to reassess the activities of the Italian Futurist movement from an international and interdisciplinary perspective, focusing on its activities and legacies in the field of poetry, painting, sculpture, theatre, cinema, advertising and politics. The essays offer exciting new readings in gender politics, aesthetics, historiography, intermediality and interdisciplinarity. They explore the works of major players of the movement as well as its lesser-known figures, and the often critical impact of Futurism on contemporary or later avant-garde movements such as Cubism, Dada and Vorticism. The publication will be of interest to scholars and students of European art, literature and cultural history, as well as to the informed general public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFuturism (Art)xItaly. 0aFuturism (Art)zItaly. 0aFuturism (Literary movement)xItalyxItaly. 0aFuturism (Literary movement)zItaly. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh  aDada art.  aFernand Leger.  aFilippo Tommaso Marinetti.  aFlorentine futurism.  aItalian futurist poetry.  aLa cucina futurista.  aLa noce.  aLe Figaro.  aManifesto del tattilismo.  aPierre Albert-Birot.  aRobert Delaunay.  aUmberto Boccioni.  aavant-garde advertisement.  aavant-garde historiography.  afuturist canons.  afuturist culture.  afuturist manifesto.  asimultaneity.  atechnological war.1 aAdamowicz, Elza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdamowicz, Elza, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAntonello, Pierpaolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerghaus, Günter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBière